Thought for 43s
I reviewed your uploaded docs and the public repo.

The core answer is this: the Sabian dynamic was solid because it had a tighter runtime contract than VRTX currently has on paper. In your docs, the winning pattern is always the same: one active engine, one prompt identity, one audio structure, one logging path, one storage model, and one deterministic output shape.
Your public GitHub README says exactly the same thing: the only active system should be circl/backend/engine/insight_engine.cjs, with no duplicate engines, no parallel systems, and no loose format. It even calls out what went wrong before: multiple engines, multiple model connectors, duplicated audio logic, and scattered core logic.

So the likely fix is not “better prompting” first. The likely fix is removing architecture drift.

What made Sabian feel like two humans talking was not magic. It was structure:

Host A had a fixed role: frame, challenge, clarify.

Sabian had a fixed role: interpret evidence, explain cause and effect, give operational guidance.

The output was short, duo-only, no monologues, 60 seconds, and ended with clear directives.

That is the part you need to bring over exactly.

The biggest weakness I see in the VRTX material is that some documents push a richer “behavioral context + scientific knowledge sources” layer, while your doctrine and guardrails say VRTX must stay metric-first, state-driven, and non-narrative.
That tension is probably where the fluff is coming from. When the engine has too much freedom, it starts sounding like a coach. When it is forced through state classification and rule templates, it sounds like an operator.

Here is the clean fix I would make.

1. Lock the pipeline in this order

Input metrics → baseline deviations → state classification → evidence object → dialogue template → validator → audio.
Not input metrics → giant prompt → hope for a good conversation.

Your own docs already support this exact flow: collect structured input, convert to evidence model, retrieve context, generate Host A/Sabian dialogue, validate, then generate audio.

2. Make state classification the true source of truth

Do not let the model invent the day.
The model should receive something like:

primary_state: Recovery Compromised Day

dominant_signals: HRV suppressed 18%, RHR elevated 6 bpm, sleep deficit 74 min

profile_modifiers: high decision load, normal work schedule, caffeine later, trains yes

allowed_rule_buckets: hydration, caffeine containment, meal composition, load reduction, sleep repair

That matches your VRTX guardrails and state framework: one primary state, deterministic thresholds, no hybrid storytelling.

3. Stop asking the model to “be conversational”
Ask it to fill a rigid stage structure.

The best form is:

Host A: one clean framing line

Sabian: one evidence explanation line

Host A: one challenge/question

Sabian: one direct operational response

Sabian: 4–6 rules

That is exactly how the repo README defines the strict audio structure, and it is why Sabian felt controlled instead of fluffy.

4. Put validator enforcement before audio generation
Reject output if any of these happen:

monologue

more than 2 Sabian sentences per turn

praise/shame language

predictive language like “you will”

generic wellness language

rules without cause-and-effect

no final 4–6 directives

Those checks are already implied by the guardrails doc and should be hard failures, not suggestions.

5. Keep only high-signal profile context
Your own internal docs are right on this point: do not clutter the profile. Keep just the fields wearables cannot see but that materially change interpretation, like occupation load, work schedule, care load, travel, caffeine timing, diet identity, alcohol bucket, and training intent.
That gives the engine enough context to say something like “protein in first meal” or “hold caffeine to early window” without becoming a lifestyle diary.

On the integration choice:

For V1, connect Fitbit Developer API first. Then add Health Connect later as a normalization layer.

Why:

Your repo and launch docs are already built around Fitbit-first: Fitbit OAuth, daily ingest, Supabase, cron, score, insight, audio, Hive. That is the active system described in both your docs and the public README.
Health Connect is valuable, but it is best as the Android aggregation layer after the core engine is stable.

Also, the technical tradeoff is clear:

Fitbit Web API gives you a server-readable OAuth pipeline for sleep, heart rate, resting heart rate, activity, and some intraday data, which fits your current backend architecture. Fitbit’s intraday heart-rate endpoint is official, but third-party access to intraday for other users requires approval, and intraday is limited to the authorized user and short windows. 

Health Connect is excellent for Android normalization and supports data types such as sleep sessions, heart rate, HRV RMSSD, resting heart rate, oxygen saturation, and steps, but it is device/app ecosystem infrastructure, not a clean drop-in replacement for your current server-centric Fitbit pipeline. It is especially relevant as Google Fit APIs are being deprecated in 2026. 

So the decision is:

V1 winner: Fitbit Developer API
because it matches your current Sabian/VRTX backend shape.

V2 expansion: Health Connect
to unify Android sources and reduce dependence on one wearable source.

One more important point: do not build VRTX around Fitbit Premium concepts like readiness/stress scores. Your internal docs are right to warn against that. Fitbit app features do not always map to public API access, and your engine should build its own explainable readiness/state model anyway.
That keeps VRTX differentiated and makes the insight transparent instead of black-box.

The clearest diagnosis I can give without seeing the bad test output itself is this:

Your weak output is probably happening because the model is being asked to generate insight from too much raw context and not enough structured evidence.
Sabian worked when the engine did the thinking first and the model did the speaking second.
Right now VRTX looks at risk of reversing that.

So the practical fix is:

lock one engine only

use Fitbit first

compute state before prompting

pass only evidence + allowed rule categories into the prompt

enforce duo-template validation

discard any output that sounds like coaching copy

That is how you get back to “two humans talking” instead of fluff.

